<subSubSection lastPageId="30" lastPageNumber="31" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1437,1400,2039]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1400,1426]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Comments.</emphasis>
Comparing the original species descriptions, the redescription of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schrottky" authorityYear="1909" box="[1092,1246,1400,1427]" class="Insecta" family="Hymenoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Odontochlora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amphitrite">
<emphasis box="[1092,1246,1400,1427]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">O. amphitrite</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Dalmazzo, M. &amp; Roig-Alsina, A." pageId="29" pageNumber="30" pagination="15 - 32" refId="ref73683" refString="Dalmazzo, M. &amp; Roig-Alsina, A. (2011) Revision of the species of the New World genus Augochlora (Hymenoptera, Halictidae) occurring in the southern temperate areas of its range. Zootaxa, 2750, 15 - 32. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 2750.1.2" type="journal article" year="2011">Dalmazzo &amp; Roig-Alsina (2011)</bibRefCitation>
, the images of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Smith. A" authorityYear="1853" box="[552,783,1436,1462]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Augochlora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="daphnis">
<emphasis box="[552,783,1436,1462]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Augochlora daphnis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
type and the examined material we concluded that there were no consistent characters supporting the hypothesis that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schrottky" authorityYear="1909" box="[847,1000,1472,1499]" class="Insecta" family="Hymenoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Odontochlora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amphitrite">
<emphasis box="[847,1000,1472,1499]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">O. amphitrite</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Smith. A" authorityYear="1853" box="[1059,1181,1472,1499]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Augochlora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="daphnis">
<emphasis box="[1059,1181,1472,1499]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">A. daphnis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
correspond to distinct species. The same interpretation was given by the personal annotations taken by Father J. S. Moure when examining the type of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Smith. A" authorityYear="1853" box="[320,440,1544,1571]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Augochlora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="daphnis">
<emphasis box="[320,440,1544,1571]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">A. daphnis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
during his visit to BMNH. We examined photographs of the 
<typeStatus box="[1124,1222,1544,1570]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">holotype</typeStatus>
and more than 
<specimenCount pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="male">115 male</specimenCount>
specimens to conclude that the yellowish tegula cited by 
<bibRefCitation author="Dalmazzo, M. &amp; Roig-Alsina, A." box="[868,1241,1580,1607]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" pagination="15 - 32" refId="ref73683" refString="Dalmazzo, M. &amp; Roig-Alsina, A. (2011) Revision of the species of the New World genus Augochlora (Hymenoptera, Halictidae) occurring in the southern temperate areas of its range. Zootaxa, 2750, 15 - 32. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 2750.1.2" type="journal article" year="2011">Dalmazzo &amp; Roig-Alsina (2011)</bibRefCitation>
along with other characteristics only represents intraspecific variation. Furthermore, no other similar species has been recorded in 
<collectingCountry box="[151,250,1653,1679]" name="Uruguay" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Uruguay</collectingCountry>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Smith. A" authorityYear="1853" box="[262,383,1652,1679]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Augochlora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="daphnis">
<emphasis box="[262,383,1652,1679]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">A. daphnis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
type locality. Thus, even 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schrottky" authorityYear="1909" box="[673,822,1652,1679]" class="Insecta" family="Hymenoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Odontochlora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amphitrite">
<emphasis box="[673,822,1652,1679]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">A. amphitrite</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
being a very common name in literature, we conclude that it is mandatory to synonymize this name under 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Smith. A" authorityYear="1853" box="[733,853,1688,1715]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Augochlora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="daphnis">
<emphasis box="[733,853,1688,1715]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">A. daphnis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Father J. S. Moure’s 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moure" authorityYear="1941" box="[1100,1307,1688,1715]" class="Insecta" family="Hymenoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Odontochlora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dolichocephala">
<emphasis box="[1100,1307,1688,1715]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">O. dolichocephala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
type corresponds to a bluish specimen with a slightly narrowed head but falling in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Smith. A" authorityYear="1853" box="[964,1084,1724,1751]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Augochlora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="daphnis">
<emphasis box="[964,1084,1724,1751]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">A. daphnis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
morphological variation space. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schrottky" authorityYear="1909" box="[151,359,1760,1786]" class="Insecta" family="Hymenoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Odontochlora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="styx">
<emphasis box="[151,359,1760,1786]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Odontochlora styx</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schrottky" authorityYear="1909" box="[373,461,1760,1787]" class="Insecta" family="Hymenoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Odontochlora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lethe">
<emphasis box="[373,461,1760,1787]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">O. lethe</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schrottky" authorityYear="1909" box="[515,610,1760,1787]" class="Insecta" family="Hymenoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Odontochlora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="thebe">
<emphasis box="[515,610,1760,1787]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">O. thebe</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were already considered as junior synonyms with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schrottky" authorityYear="1909" box="[1177,1328,1760,1787]" class="Insecta" family="Hymenoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Odontochlora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amphitrite">
<emphasis box="[1177,1328,1760,1787]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">O. amphitrite</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by previous authors (
<bibRefCitation author="Dalmazzo, M. &amp; Roig-Alsina, A." box="[294,647,1796,1823]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" pagination="15 - 32" refId="ref73683" refString="Dalmazzo, M. &amp; Roig-Alsina, A. (2011) Revision of the species of the New World genus Augochlora (Hymenoptera, Halictidae) occurring in the southern temperate areas of its range. Zootaxa, 2750, 15 - 32. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 2750.1.2" type="journal article" year="2011">Dalmazzo &amp; Roig-Alsina 2011</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Lepeco, A. &amp; Goncalves, R. B." box="[659,963,1796,1823]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" pagination="662 - 670" refId="ref75476" refString="Lepeco, A. &amp; Goncalves, R. B. (2018) The Colour and the Shape: Morphological Variation on a Facultatively Eusocial Bee Augochlora (Augochlora) amphitrite (Schrottky). Sociobiology, 65, 662 - 670. https: // doi. org / 10.13102 / sociobiology. v 65 i 4.3388" type="journal article" year="2018">Lepeco &amp; Gonçalves 2018</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1437,1400,2039]" lastBlockId="30.[151,1436,151,393]" lastPageId="30" lastPageNumber="31" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
For species redescription and more comments on type material see 
<bibRefCitation author="Dalmazzo, M. &amp; Roig-Alsina, A." box="[940,1306,1832,1859]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" pagination="15 - 32" refId="ref73683" refString="Dalmazzo, M. &amp; Roig-Alsina, A. (2011) Revision of the species of the New World genus Augochlora (Hymenoptera, Halictidae) occurring in the southern temperate areas of its range. Zootaxa, 2750, 15 - 32. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 2750.1.2" type="journal article" year="2011">Dalmazzo &amp; Roig-Alsina (2011)</bibRefCitation>
. Nest structure and life-history were studied by 
<bibRefCitation author="Sakagami, S. F. &amp; Moure, J. S." box="[568,872,1868,1895]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" pagination="119 - 138" refId="ref76679" refString="Sakagami, S. F. &amp; Moure, J. S. (1967) Additional observations on the nesting habits of some Brazilian Halictine bees. Mushi, 40 (10), 119 - 138." type="journal article" year="1967">Sakagami &amp; Moure (1967)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Dalmazzo, M. &amp; Roig-Alsina, A." box="[927,1290,1868,1895]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" pagination="17 - 29" refId="ref73740" refString="Dalmazzo, M. &amp; Roig-Alsina, A. (2012) Nest structure and notes on the social behavior of Augochlora amphitrite (Schrottky) (Hymenoptera, Halictidae). Journal of Hymenoptera Research, 26, 17 - 29. https: // doi. org / 10.3897 / jhr. 26.2440" type="journal article" year="2012">Dalmazzo &amp; Roig-Alsina (2012</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Dalmazzo, M. &amp; Roig-Alsina, A." box="[1302,1375,1869,1895]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" pagination="773 - 776" refId="ref73854" refString="Dalmazzo, M. &amp; Roig-Alsina, A. (2018 a) Primitively Eusocial Behavior Observed in Colonies of Augochlora amphitrite (Hymenoptera: Halictidae) Reared in Laboratory. Sociobiology, 65 (4), 773 - 776. https: // doi. org / 10.13102 / sociobiology. v 65 i 4.3484" type="journal article" year="2018">2018a</bibRefCitation>
), diet preferences by 
<bibRefCitation author="Dalmazzo, M. &amp; Vossler, F. G." box="[323,643,1904,1931]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" pagination="253 - 262" refId="ref73973" refString="Dalmazzo, M. &amp; Vossler, F. G. (2015 a) Pollen host selection by a broadly polylectic halictid bee in relation to resource availability. Arthropod-Plant Interactions, 9 (3), 253 - 262. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 11829 - 015 - 9364 - 1" type="journal article" year="2015">Dalmazzo &amp; Vossler (2015a</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Dalmazzo, M. &amp; Vossler, F. G." box="[655,730,1904,1931]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" pagination="478 - 488" refId="ref74032" refString="Dalmazzo, M. &amp; Vossler, F. G. (2015 b) Assessment of the pollen diet in a wood-dwelling augochlorine bee (Halictidae) using different approaches. Apidologie, 46 (4), 478 - 488. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 13592 - 014 - 0337 - 7" type="journal article" year="2015">2015b</bibRefCitation>
), and morphological variation by 
<bibRefCitation author="Lepeco, A. &amp; Goncalves, R. B." box="[1110,1432,1904,1931]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" pagination="662 - 670" refId="ref75476" refString="Lepeco, A. &amp; Goncalves, R. B. (2018) The Colour and the Shape: Morphological Variation on a Facultatively Eusocial Bee Augochlora (Augochlora) amphitrite (Schrottky). Sociobiology, 65, 662 - 670. https: // doi. org / 10.13102 / sociobiology. v 65 i 4.3388" type="journal article" year="2018">Lepeco &amp; Gonçalves (2018)</bibRefCitation>
. A gynandromorph specimen was described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Alvarez, L. J. &amp; Lucia, M. &amp; Ramello, P. J. &amp; Abrahamovich, A. H." box="[681,922,1940,1967]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" pagination="447 - 450" refId="ref73111" refString="Alvarez, L. J., Lucia, M., Ramello, P. J. &amp; Abrahamovich, A. H. (2014) Description of two new cases of gynandromorphism in Paratrigona Schwarz and Augochlora Smith (Hymenoptera: Apidae and Halictidae). Zootaxa, 3889 (3), 447 - 450. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3889.3.7" type="journal article" year="2014">
Alvarez 
<emphasis box="[778,836,1940,1966]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">et al.</emphasis>
(2014)
</bibRefCitation>
. Color and structural variation in this species were already noted by 
<bibRefCitation author="Dalmazzo, M. &amp; Roig-Alsina, A." box="[415,788,1976,2003]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" pagination="15 - 32" refId="ref73683" refString="Dalmazzo, M. &amp; Roig-Alsina, A. (2011) Revision of the species of the New World genus Augochlora (Hymenoptera, Halictidae) occurring in the southern temperate areas of its range. Zootaxa, 2750, 15 - 32. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 2750.1.2" type="journal article" year="2011">Dalmazzo &amp; Roig-Alsina (2011)</bibRefCitation>
and by 
<bibRefCitation author="Lepeco, A. &amp; Goncalves, R. B." box="[883,1210,1976,2003]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" pagination="662 - 670" refId="ref75476" refString="Lepeco, A. &amp; Goncalves, R. B. (2018) The Colour and the Shape: Morphological Variation on a Facultatively Eusocial Bee Augochlora (Augochlora) amphitrite (Schrottky). Sociobiology, 65, 662 - 670. https: // doi. org / 10.13102 / sociobiology. v 65 i 4.3388" type="journal article" year="2018">Lepeco &amp; Gonçalves (2018)</bibRefCitation>
, certainly being the reason why C. Schrottky described the species four times in the same paper. This may be the unluckiest species of the genus, since the type series of four species names were probably lost in a Paraguayan civil war (
<bibRefCitation author="Rasmussen, C. &amp; Garcete-Barrett, B. R. &amp; Goncalves, R. B." pageId="30" pageNumber="31" pagination="1 - 50" refId="ref76563" refString="Rasmussen, C., Garcete-Barrett, B. R. &amp; Goncalves, R. B. (2009) Curt Schrottky (1874 - 1937): South American entomology at the beginning of the 20 th century (Hymenoptera, Lepidoptera, Diptera). Zootaxa, 2282 (1), 1 - 50. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 2282.1.1" type="journal article" year="2009">
Rasmussen 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">et al.</emphasis>
2009
</bibRefCitation>
) and the 
<typeStatus box="[347,445,187,213]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Smith. A" authorityYear="1853" box="[482,602,187,213]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Augochlora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="daphnis">
<emphasis box="[482,602,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">A. daphnis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
had its head replaced by a glued 
<taxonomicName box="[973,1148,187,213]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Augochloropsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[973,1148,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Augochloropsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
head (Dalmazzo &amp; Roig-Asina 2011).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="30" pageNumber="31" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1436,151,393]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,258,284]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Distribution.</emphasis>
This is a very common species in southern South America, occurring in the Brazilian states of Minas Gerais, Paraná, Rio Grande do Sul, Santa Catarina, and S„o Paulo. In 
<collectingCountry box="[1029,1140,295,321]" name="Argentina" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Argentina</collectingCountry>
the species is recorded in the provinces of 
<collectingRegion box="[341,494,331,357]" country="Argentina" name="Ciudad Autonoma de Buenos Aires" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Buenos Aires</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[506,580,331,357]" country="Argentina" name="Chaco" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Chaco</collectingRegion>
, Córdoba, 
<collectingRegion box="[704,826,331,357]" country="Argentina" name="Entre Rios" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Entre Ríos</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[838,900,331,357]" country="Argentina" name="Jujuy" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Jujuy</collectingRegion>
, Misiones, 
<collectingRegion box="[1029,1131,331,357]" country="Argentina" name="San Luis" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">San Luís</collectingRegion>
, and 
<collectingRegion box="[1191,1292,331,357]" country="Argentina" name="Santa Fe" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Santa Fé</collectingRegion>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Smith. A" authorityYear="1853" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Augochlora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="daphnis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Augochlora daphnis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also recorded in 
<collectingCountry box="[458,562,367,393]" name="Paraguay" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Paraguay</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[617,717,367,393]" name="Uruguay" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Uruguay</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
